Korone? (The name "科伦" is likely a transliteration of a proper noun, such as a person's name, place, or brand. It could be translated as "Korone" or "Kolone" depending on the context. If it's a known name, please provide more context for an accurate translation.)
It was 4:30 in the morning in Italy. Col. Kolen hated waking up so early. Mainly because he was responsible for waking up the rest of the squad. He got out of bed silently, put on his combat gear, fastened his assault vest, and carefully packed his belongings from the storage cabinet. He gently picked up a small, special box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and attached his helmet to a small hook on his belt. The helmet was equipped with a full set of gear, including a respirator, goggles, and other necessary items. After checking his ammunition pouches, he quietly stepped out of the barracks, his boots making a crunching sound on the muddy and icy ground.
He took out a lighter from his jacket pocket and a cigarette from another pocket. After lighting the cigarette, he took a gentle puff and then opened the door. In the past week, he had to think hard just to wake up his subordinates. He no longer used the preset alarm clock because it didn't ring half the time, and all he could hear was a faint hissing sound from the speaker.
"Time to wake them up?" Colton turned around and saw Captain Nemitz approaching.
"Yes," Corran replied.
"What method are you planning to use this time?"
Colin hadn't even had time to answer when the door opened, and Harris, Kreis, and several others rushed out, already dressed and ready.
"Good morning," said Cres.
" What woke you up?" Corran asked.
"First of all, we really don't want to see what methods you're going to use to wake everyone up today. Second, the first squad to get up can have priority for breakfast," said a soldier named Ravik. "You know, how terrible that breakfast is."
Korren said, "You're right, Corporal Ravik." He reached out and pressed the switch. Instantly, a piercing alarm sounded throughout the barracks. He heard shouts inside, accompanied by a flurry of hurried footsteps.
"Good heavens, Valturi," Nemich said. "I thought they should have learned by now to wake up with you."
"Brothers from my new recruit training camp did it," Corran pointed to Harris, Cres, and Ravik. "But to be honest, their squad leaders and platoon commanders knew to get up before the soldiers."
A few seconds later, the rest of the soldiers in the squad ran out. They were all dressed and ready. Some of the new recruits looked drowsy, while others appeared very annoyed.
"Good morning, everyone," Colen said cheerfully.
"Forgive me for speaking frankly, sir, but why did you wake us up in that way?" asked a突击队员 (corporal).
"Because those ordinary alarm clocks are just garbage. And Daybreak never sleeps in," said Corrin.
"Take your personal belongings," Colonel Kolen continued. As a lieutenant and the deputy commander of the platoon, he had the responsibility to assist Captain Borlatan Xiao in supervising and leading the platoon. "We won't be returning. Sergeants and lieutenants, you and your squads have 15 minutes for a final check and to bring along today's rations."
The members of Exodus squad quickly dispersed. They were part of the Second Assault Regiment of the Second Corps. Before the merger, they had been two separate squads, Cohort and Dagger. This was an elite squad, and Colonel Kolen felt complex emotions about being promoted to the rank of lieutenant, for many reasons.
Colonel Korm and Lieutenant Commander Nimitz walked side by side along the brightly lit roads of the base, whose lights were powered by generators. Most of the lights were red, helping them avoid enemy bombers. To counter them, Daybreak had begun employing "wild weasel" tactics both in the air and on the ground.
"Another day, a new mission for the Hell's Vanguard," Nimitz dryly chuckled. "Where are they going to send us this time?"
"It's some frontline base outside the city of Ianlos. We were sent to support the ground assault," Corran said, taking a drag of his cigarette. He was a little resentful that Kress had gotten him hooked on smoking, but thinking back on the past year, they had gone through countless battles, and he had come to accept it. So he said nothing.
"Terrible. The front lines are really tough," Nimitz muttered. "All the messages coming from here are about 'supporting the war, aiding the Kursk front.' Why not support the Holland front instead?"
"Good talk, brother," Corran said, flicking the butt of his cigarette into the mud. "We're going with the first armor squad—no walking. Captain Xiao should be there."
"Did Lieutenant Xiao let us ride with him?" Nimitz asked in surprise.
"Yes. To be honest, he's not as bad as I imagined. I mean, he's not great, but he's not that讨厌 either."
Cole raised his thumb and index finger, pressing against the microphone on his throat, while shifting his backpack onto his back. "All units of Exodus, assemble at the west district vehicle depot after completing the mission. We will depart with the first armor platoon at 05:00."
Every few seconds, he would receive replies from the squad leaders. When they first arrived, Harris, Cress, and Ravek were all junior non-commissioned officers. Since their basic training on Earth, the four of them have been close friends. Cole felt like he had known them for a long time, even though it had been less than two years. They were all squad leaders, but since a week ago, when the front sergeant was shot by Daybreak snipers and had to retire due to injuries, Cress began leading the second squad.
As they approached the vehicle depot, Colonel Kolen and Admiral Nimitz's eyes fell upon roughly eight Cronos main battle tanks and four Stryker armored vehicles. Crew members were bustling around, ensuring their war machines were all functioning properly. Kolen quickly spotted Captain Borlatan Xiao in the crowd, who was engaged in conversation with the commander of the armored platoon. As they approached, Captain Xiao glanced at them and came forward, his usual indifferent expression revealing no emotion.
"Ensign Nimitz... Lieutenant Valturi..." he said, Corran slowed his steps, Captain Xiao looked at Corran's holstered pistol, then looked up. "Has the squad already been prepared?"
